What led to Transformers?¶

RNN¶

  • Vanishing/exploding gradient problem

Backprop Through Time¶

  • Stopped working when sentences were too long
  • Onward!

LSTM¶

  • Long Short Term Memory
  • Smaller chance of exploding/vanishing gradients
  • Longer term dependencies!
  • Gates -> Choose what to remember, and forget!
  • Sadly, these too broke down when it came to longer sentences
  • Followed up by many attempts to fix this
    • Bi-directional
    • Variants of the gates
    • Gradient Clipping
    • Convolutional RNNs
    • GRU

GRU¶

  • Gated Recurrent Unit
  • Input, Forget gate
  • Simplified LSTM -> Faster!
  • But performs worse in many cases ):
  • And thus we have, drumroll

Intermission - What is the problem?¶

  • Very long sentences
  • Forgets things after a while
  • Not very great at understanding context
    • Let's eat, Grandma, I am starving.
    • Let's eat Grandma, I am starving.
  • What exactly is important in a sentence?
    • The boy plays with the ball
    • Eating a mango, she says, hi!
  • How do we solve this?

In Images¶

Now for text¶

How?¶

  • Every word -> Embedding
  • Represent in vector space
  • The closer the "distance", the closer the words are
    • Eg: King, Throne ; Food, Dosa
  • Weighted sum over all the embedding vectors
  • Weighted by their normalized dot products
  • How related the words in the sequence are

from numpy import array
from numpy import random
from numpy import dot
from scipy.special import softmax
import seaborn as sns

# encoder representations of four different words
# word1, word2, word3, word4 = vecs

# stacking the word embeddings into a single array
# words = array([word_1, word_2, word_3, word_4])
words= vecs.copy()
sz = vecs[0].size
# generating the weight matrices
random.seed(42)
W_Q = random.randint(sz, size=(sz, sz))
W_K = random.randint(sz, size=(sz, sz))
W_V = random.randint(sz, size=(sz, sz))

# generating the queries, keys and values
Q = words @ W_Q
K = words @ W_K
V = words @ W_V

# scoring the query vectors against all key vectors
scores = Q @ K.transpose()

# computing the weights by a softmax operation
weights = softmax(scores / K.shape[1] ** 0.5, axis=1)

# computing the attention by a weighted sum of the value vectors
attention = weights @ V
